\begin{CRITIC}
*   **Data-Hypothesis Alignment**: The proposed "selectivity compression" ratio (High-Tariff / Any HE) is mathematically sound but risks conflating two distinct phenomena: institutional expansion and demographic access. Because the dataset is aggregate, you cannot distinguish between "elite institutions becoming more exclusive" and "non-elite institutions absorbing the bulk of the growth in participation."
*   **Feasibility & Noise**: The ratio is highly sensitive to the denominator (overall HE progression). If a demographic group sees a massive increase in "Any HE" participation (e.g., due to policy shifts), the ratio will artificially deflate, potentially masking an absolute increase in high-tariff access.
*   **Redundancy Check**: This is a derivative of the "High-Tariff Gap" already requested in the research aim. It adds complexity without necessarily providing a clearer signal than the absolute gap and the ratio of rates already planned.
*   **Physical Reality**: The "selectivity compression" metric assumes a linear relationship between general HE access and high-tariff access that may not exist.
*   **Strategic Pivot**: Instead of a "selectivity compression" ratio, calculate the **"High-Tariff Conversion Rate"** (High-Tariff Students / Total HE Students) for each group. This directly measures the *compositional* shift of the HE population per group. To avoid the "denominator trap," you must present this alongside the absolute `high_tariff_progression_rate` to ensure you aren't misinterpreting a surge in non-selective participation as a decline in elite access.
\end{CRITIC}


